  "text": "## Kubernetes: Lease-Based Leader Election\n\nKubernetes implements leader election through a **lease-based mechanism** in `staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/leaderelection.go`. The core component is the `LeaderElector` struct, which manages a leadership claim on a Kubernetes Lease resource.\n\n### Kubernetes Election Flow\n\nThe election process follows this sequence:\n\n1. **Initialization**: `NewLeaderElector()` creates a LeaderElector with a `LeaderElectionConfig` containing:\n   - `Lock`: A `LeaseLock` (defined in `staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/resourcelock/leaselock.go`) that represents a Kubernetes Lease API object\n   - `LeaseDuration`: How long the lease is valid (default 15 seconds)\n   - `RenewDeadline`: Time to renew before giving up (default 10 seconds)\n   - `RetryPeriod`: Interval between retries (default 2 seconds)\n\n2. **Leadership Acquisition**: `LeaderElector.Run()` calls `acquire()`, which repeatedly calls `tryAcquireOrRenew(ctx)` until successful. This method:\n   - Attempts to create a new LeaderElectionRecord in the Lease if it doesn't exist\n   - Updates the Lease with HolderIdentity, AcquireTime, and RenewTime fields\n   - Uses fast-path optimization: if already leading, optimistically updates the record\n   - Falls back to slow-path (full read-modify-write) on conflict\n\n3. **Leadership Renewal**: Once acquired, `Run()` calls `renew()`, which continuously attempts to renew the lease within `RenewDeadline` using `PollUntilContextTimeout()`. The renewal checks:\n   - `isLeaseValid()` verifies the lease hasn't expired by checking: `observedTime + LeaseDurationSeconds > now`\n   - If renewal fails within RenewDeadline, the process stops leading\n\n### Kubernetes Failover and Re-election\n\nFailover is **time-based** and deterministic:\n\n1. **Leader Detection**: When a leader dies, no renewal happens. Other candidates wait for `LeaseDuration` to expire (time since last successful renewal).\n2. **Re-election Trigger**: Once `LeaseDuration` expires, any candidate can call `tryAcquireOrRenew()` which checks: if `len(HolderIdentity) > 0 && isLeaseValid(now) && !IsLeader()` returns false (lease expired), it attempts to acquire.\n3. **Transition Tracking**: `maybeReportTransition()` triggers the `OnNewLeader()` callback when leadership changes detected through `LeaderElectionRecord.HolderIdentity`.\n\nThe implementation explicitly documents that it does NOT provide strict fencing (only one holder), relying instead on timestamps and local clocks. It's tolerant to clock skew but not to high clock skew rates.\n\n---\n\n## etcd: Raft-Based Leader Election\n\netcd implements leader election through the **Raft consensus algorithm** at the server level, with an optional client-side election API wrapper.\n\n### etcd Server-Level Raft Election\n\nThe core Raft implementation is in `server/etcdserver/raft.go` in the `raftNode` struct:\n\n1. **Node Initialization**: `newRaftNode(cfg raftNodeConfig)` creates a raftNode that wraps a `raft.Node` with:\n   - Periodic `tick()` calls (based on heartbeat interval, typically ~100ms)\n   - A transport layer for sending/receiving Raft messages\n   - Storage layer for persisting Raft state\n\n2. **Election Loop**: `raftNode.start()` launches a goroutine that:\n   - Calls `tick()` on each heartbeat ticker interval\n   - Processes `Ready()` states from the Raft node\n   - Detects leadership changes via `rd.SoftState.Lead`\n   - Calls `updateLeadership(newLeader)` when leadership transitions occur\n   - The Raft state machine internally handles campaign timeout logic\n\n3. **Leadership State**: Leadership is determined by the Raft node's internal state:\n   - `rd.RaftState == raft.StateLeader` indicates the node is now leader\n   - `rd.SoftState.Lead` contains the leader's node ID\n   - Metrics track: `isLeader.Set(1)` for leader, `leaderChanges.Inc()` on transitions\n\n### etcd Client-Side Election API\n\nFor application-level leader election, etcd provides `client/v3/concurrency/election.go`:\n\n1. **Campaign**: `Election.Campaign(ctx, val)` implements client-side election:\n   - Uses a transaction: `If(v3.Compare(v3.CreateRevision(k), \"=\", 0))`\n   - Puts a key `\"%s%x\".format(keyPrefix, lease_id)` with the election value\n   - Waits for all keys with lower CreateRevision to be deleted via `waitDeletes()`\n   - Only becomes leader when all previous candidates resign\n\n2. **Proclaim**: `Election.Proclaim(ctx, val)` allows leader to announce new values with transactional safety\n\n3. **Resign**: `Election.Resign(ctx)` releases leadership, allowing next candidate to become leader\n\n### etcd Failover and Re-election\n\nFailover is **automatic and consensus-based**:\n\n1. **Failure Detection**: When a leader fails:\n   - Followers stop receiving heartbeats within election timeout (~150-300ms in Raft)\n   - The Raft state machine automatically initiates `Campaign()` internally\n   - Raft protocol ensures safe state transitions through majority quorum\n\n2. **Leader Election**: The Raft consensus algorithm guarantees:\n   - A term increments on each election\n   - A node becomes candidate, increments term, and sends RequestVote RPCs\n   - First candidate to get majority votes becomes leader\n   - All entries from previous leader are committed before new entries\n\n3. **Leadership Transition Detection**: `server/etcdserver/raft.go` lines 186-204:\n   - `newLeader := rd.SoftState.Lead != raft.None && rh.getLead() != rd.SoftState.Lead`\n   - On transition: `leaderChanges.Inc()` and `hasLeader.Set(1/0)`\n   - Resets contention detector with `r.td.Reset()`\n\n4. **Member Changes**: Configuration changes are replayed as `raftpb.EntryConfChange` entries before followers can participate, ensuring consistency during membership updates.\n\n---\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | etcd |\n|--------|-----------|------|\n| **Mechanism** | Lease-based on API objects | Raft consensus algorithm |\n| **Failure Detection** | Time-based (LeaseDuration) | Election timeout (async heartbeat) |\n| **Failover Speed** | Deterministic, ~LeaseDuration (15s default) | Sub-second (depends on election timeout) |\n| **Fencing** | Not guaranteed (time-based only) | Strong consistency via quorum |\n| **Storage** | Kubernetes Lease API | Raft log + persistent storage |\n| **Applicability** | Controller managers, schedulers | Cluster-wide consensus, core state |\n| **Client Integration** | Uses Lock interface with retries | Raft consensus integrated in server |\n"

